    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.5.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, I'm not sure Vim has support of attaching UIs with msgpack \n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 20.04.3 LTS\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nNeoray UI 0.0.9\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color, but it's not applicable I would gess\n\n### Installation\n\nappimage\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nHave a plugin that displays a hint, I use\r\n\r\n```\r\nPlug 'neoclide/coc.nvim', {'branch': 'release'}\r\nPlug 'fatih/vim-go'\r\n```\r\n\r\nTo display inter errrors:\r\n![Screenshot from 2021-09-03 00-01-18](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/244042/132332839-048959f5-2939-4148-bf22-12d52c6f1895.png)\r\n\r\nThen switch to another window (`gt` or `:tabe`). Client receives `win_hide` event, which should not be sent when `AttachUI` in go client was not called with `options[\"ext_multigrid\"] = true`. \r\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNo `win_hide` event is received because it is a multigrid event.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\n`win_hide` is received, which is unexpected for client.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "It's a bit tricky because the compositor uses \"multigrid\" for floats internally for the TUI (currently using a side-channel but \"some time\" it is suppposed to use win_pos/hide events like any UI), and we don't filter events per UI. Though note that neovim may add new UI events at any time, so a UI should not assert against an unexpected event.",
